summary:
• Gas Supply Agreement: 7-year deal with GGNZ Ltd for up to 7PJ gas annually, effective 1 October 2025 (option to extend +3 years).
  • Diversification Benefit: Reduces single-field reliance for retail gas customers and electricity generation.
  • Renewable Impact: Expected 200–300GWh gas-fueled electricity generation annually, maintaining ~98% renewable generation portfolio (post-Taranaki CC closure in late 2025).
  • Strategic Alignment: Supports NZ businesses transitioning from gas to renewables, consistent with net-zero generation by 2035 goal.
  • Investment Context: Part of >$2B committed renewable energy infrastructure investments over past 4 years.

No material capital markets actions (e.g., raising, trading halt) identified.

• Director Share Purchase: Hartley Atkinson (Director) acquired 200,000 AFT ordinary shares via on-market purchases at an average price of NZ$2.83/share (total ~NZ$566,000).
  • Post-Transaction Holdings:
  • Atkinson Family Trust (jointly controlled): 72,259,496 shares (up from 72,059,496).
  • Personal beneficial holdings: 867,826 shares.

No other material information identified.

• May 2025 Traffic Highlights:
  • Group capacity down 2.7% YoY due to reduced aircraft availability from engine maintenance.
  • YTD underlying RASK improved 2.0% YoY (Long Haul +2.8%, Short Haul +0.4%).

  • Passenger load factor increased to 82.0% (vs. 79.5% prior year).

  • Key Operational Updates:

  • Summer Capacity Boost: 1.7M additional Tasman/Pacific seats (Oct 2025–Mar 2026), 8% more premium seats.
  • New Route: Christchurch–Adelaide (seasonal, 15K seats, from Oct 2025).
  • Long-Haul Expansion: 34K additional North America seats; 20.5K more premium seats network-wide.

  • Fleet Expansion: Two new A321neo aircraft (70K annual seats) entering service mid-2025.

  • Strategic Partnerships:

  • $700K marketing investment with Air China/Tourism NZ to stimulate Chinese travel demand (+33% premium seats on Shanghai route).

No material capital markets activity identified (e.g., no raising, M&A, or material financial guidance).

• Updated FY25 uNPAT guidance: Expected at lower end of analyst range ($27.0M–$34.4M), reflecting pressure from global RV sales challenges and reduced manufacturing volumes.
  • FY26 outlook:
  • Opening net debt ~$500M (excluding IFRS 16 leases).
  • Double-digit rental revenue growth in all markets except USA (single-digit decline).
  • NZ/AU forward rentals +25% YoY; USA bookings recovering post-Liberation Day dip.
  • Potential goodwill impairment: NZ$36M (USA business) under review due to uncertain travel outlook. Other non-cash one-offs possible (statutory NPAT impact only).
  • Covenants unaffected by potential impairments.

Key risks: Weak USA demand, manufacturing slowdown, pending impairment decision.
Catalysts: Future announcements on initiatives to address cyclical challenges.

No material capital raising, trading halt, or liquidity events identified.
